### Forbidden Classes
The **Artificer**, **Bard**, and **Sorcerer** do not exist as player classes in Dark Sun. 

#### Artificer

Athas is a barren, magic-starved world where the inventions and enchantments of artificers would fundamentally clash with the characterization of magic in this setting.

#### Bard

While bards exist, they are known better as entertainers leading double lives as spies and assassins who would not want the attention that magic brings in Athas.



#### Sorcerer 
Having innate arcane magic within yourself as the source does not work in the setting of Athas. Any mention of Sorcerers in Dark Sun is simply another name for powerful Arcanists (such as the Sorcerer-Kings). 

<div class='descriptive'>
 
##### Changes to Classes and their Archetypes
Many of the classes represented on the following pages have a curated selection of archetypes, and may feature revisions to their class and archetype features. All changes were made in the name of both balance and consistency with the lore of Athas. 
 </div>
 

{{pageNumber,auto}}
\page



![Background image](https://i.ibb.co/xHfBSgX/Arcanist-splash-page.jpg){position:absolute,bottom:0,left:0,height:100%,width:100%}  

\page

# Arcanist

Arcane magic is outlawed in every city-state. Yet Arcanists still study the arcane arts, whether rediscovering forbidden lore in study of ancient texts or apprenticing within ambitious cabals, drawn to the temptations of magic even at the risk of their lives. Arcanists are universally distrusted, for it is they who Athas can blame for its barren, savage state. 

Save those rare few independent spellcasters bound to the Sorcerer-Kings, Arcanists in Athas are likely revolutionaries or exiles. They must take extreme steps to hide their nature, even from those few they may trust. Many pretend at being Clerics or psionicists, for fear of the reprisals that would visit not only them, but all known to have helped or associated with their ilk. 
<div class='descriptive'>
 
##### Arcane Masteries


The study of magic is ancient, stretching back to the earliest mortal discoveries. Once, Arcanists were trained in vast academies with repositories of knowledge beyond the comprehension of any living Athasian. Today, Arcanists are defined by action more than philsophy, and the old schools have fallen in favor of titles which even the lowest slave can understand as both curse and warning. 


* **Caller.** Summon your whims to hand with spells focused on conjuring objects and creatures.

<br>

* **Magus.** Specialize in battle magic by empowering your spells and bolstering your defenses. 

<br>

* **Mesmer.** Hone your abilities to magically entrance and beguile
other people and monsters.

<br>

* **Mirage.** Dazzle their senses, befuddle their minds, lead them astray- you are the mirage, the illusion.

<br>

* **Necromancer.** Sap the strength of those who stand against you, and raise the dead as allies.

<br>

* **Prophet.** Master spells of
discernment, remote viewing, supernatural knowledge,
and foresight.

<br>

* **Ravager.** Use the spectacular power of the arcane to rend, incinerate, and obliterate your enemies.

<br>

* **Warder.** Deny the blow, the curse, the enemy advance- yours is the art of defense and shielding. 
</div>




\column

## Creating an Arcanist

Creating an Arcanist demands a backstory dominated by at least one extraordinary event. How did your character first come into contact with magic? How did you discover you had an aptitude for it? Do you have a natural talent, or did you simply study hard and practice incessantly? Did you encounter a magical creature or an ancient tome that taught you the basics of magic?

What drew you forth from your life of study? Did your first taste of magical knowledge leave you hungry for more? Have you received word of a secret repository of knowledge not yet plundered by any other Arcanist? Perhaps you’re simply eager to put your newfound magical skills to the test in the face of danger.


## Class Features

As an Arcanist, you gain the following class features.

#### Hit Points
**Hit Dice:**                    :: 1d6 per Arcanist level
**Hit Points at 1st Level:**     :: 6 + your Constitution modifier
**Hit Points at Higher Levels:** :: 1d6 (or 4) + your Constitution modifier per Arcanist level after 1st.

#### Proficiencies
**Armor:**   :: None
**Weapons:** :: Daggers, darts, slings, quarterstaffs, light crossbows
**Tools:**   :: None
**Saving Throws:** :: Intelligence, Wisdom
**Skills:**        :: Choose two from Arcana, Deception, History, Investigation, Medicine, Sleight of Hand, and Performance

#### Spellcasting  Ability
{{text-align:center
**Power save DC**:: = 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Intelligence modifier

**Power attack modifier**:: = your proficiency bonus + your Intelligence modifier
}}

#### Equipment
You start with the following equipment, in addition to the equipment granted by your background:
-  a simple weapon

- (*a*) a quarterstaff or (*b*) a dagger

- (*a*) a component pouch or (*b*) an arcane focus

- (*a*) a scholar’s pack or (*b*) an explorer’s pack

- A spellbook

{{pageNumber,auto}}
\page




## Spellcasting
As a student of arcane magic, you have a spellbook containing the first glimmerings of your true power. See Chapter 9 for the rules of spellcasting and Chapter 10 for the Arcanist spell list.

#### Cantrips
At 1st level, you know three cantrips of your choice from the Arcanist spell list. You learn additional Arcanist cantrips of your choice at higher levels, as shown in the Cantrips Known column of the Arcanist table.


#### Preparing and Casting Spells
The Arcanist table shows how many spell slots you have to cast your spells of 1st level and higher. To cast one of these spells, you must expend a slot of the spell’s level or higher. You regain all expended spell slots when you finish a long rest.

You prepare the list of Arcanist spells that are available for you to cast. To do so. choose a number of Arcanist spells from your spellbook equal to your Intelligence modifier + your Arcanist level (minimum of one spell). The spells must be of a level for which you have spell slots.

For example, if you're a 3rd-level Arcanist, you have four 1st-level and two 2nd-level spell slots. With an Intelligence of 16, your list of prepared spells can include six spells of 1st or 2nd level, in any combination, chosen from your spellbook. If you prepare the 1st-level spell *magic missile*, you can cast it using a 1st-level or a 2nd-level slot. Casting the spell doesn’t remove it from your list of prepared spells.

You can change your list of prepared spells when you finish a long rest. Preparing a new list of Arcanist spells requires time spent studying your spellbook and memorizing the incantations and gestures you must make to cast the spell: at least 1 minute per spell level for each spell on your list.

#### Ritual Casting
You can cast Arcanist spells as rituals if that spell has the ritual tag and you have the spell in your spellbook. The spell does not have to be prepared. 

#### Spellcasting Focus
You can use an arcane focus (found in Chapter 5) as a spellcasting focus for your Arcanist spells.

#### Learning Spells of 1st Level and Higher
Each time you gain an Arcanist level, you can add two Arcanist spells of your choice to your spellbook. Each of these spells must be of a level for which you have spell slots, as shown on the Arcanist table. On your adventures, you might find other spells that you can add to your spellbook (see the “Your Spellbook” sidebar).

#### Spellbook
At 1st level, you have a spellbook containing six 1st-level Arcanist spells of your choice.

<div class='descriptive'>
 
##### Your Spellbook
The spells that you add to your spellbook as you gain levels reflect the magic you develop as your power grows, whether from instinctual insights or spells found recorded on scrolls stolen from Templar vaults or rediscovered in dusty tomes from ancient tombs. 

***Copying a Spell into the Book.*** When you find an Arcanist spell of 1st level or higher, you can add it to your spellbook if it is of a level for which you have spell slots and if you can spare the time to decipher and copy it.

Copying a spell into your spellbook involves reproducing the basic form of the spell, then deciphering the unique system of notation used by the Arcanist who wrote it. You must practice the spell until you understand the verbal and somatic components, then transcribe it into your spellbook using your own notation. 

For each level of the spell, the process takes 2 hours and costs 50 ct. The cost represents material components you expend as you experiment with the spell to master it, as well as the fine inks needed to record it. Once you have spent this time and money, you can prepare the spell like other spells.

***Replacing the Book.*** You can copy a spell from your own spellbook into another book— for example, if you want to make a backup copy of your spellbook. This follows the same rules as copying another's work, with the material costs reduced based on your familiarity. You need spend only 1 hour and 10 ct for each level of the copied spell.

If you lose your spellbook, you can use the same procedure to transcribe the spells that you have prepared into a new spellbook. Filling out the remainder of your spellbook requires you to find new spells to do so, as normal. For this reason, many Arcanists keep backup spellbooks in a safe place.

 </div>


{{note
##### Hiding a Spellbook
Arcanists learn quickly to hide their spellbooks, keeping one step
ahead of Templar searches. They might write them on scrolls hidden within hollowed-out walking sticks and weapons, sew each page between the cloth of their cloaks and clothing, or carve the symbols onto implements of wood and bone. The more daring or desperate may even tattoo their spells onto their own skin, trading subtlety for the confidence of always having power at their fingertips. For most, it is best to find a careful hiding spot (or several) wherever they make rest.
}}

{{pageNumber,auto}}
\page

{{classTable,frame,decoration,wide
##### The Arcanist
