## Armor and Shields
Athas presents a vast tapestry made up of many different cultures, each with its own technology level. For this reason, adventurers have access to a variety of armor types, ranging from leather armor to so-ut mail to costly braxat plate armor, with several other kinds of armor in between. The Armor table collects the most commonly available types of armor found in the game and separates them into three categories: light armor, medium armor, and heavy armor. Many warriors supplement their armor with one of many kinds of shields, split between simple and martial options. 

The Armor table shows the cost, weight, and other properties of the common types of armor.

***Armor Proficiency.*** Anyone can put on a suit of armor or strap a shield to an arm. Only those proficient in the armor’s use know how to wear it effectively, however. Your class gives you proficiency with certain types of armor. If you wear armor that you lack proficiency with, you have disadvantage on any ability check, saving throw, or attack roll that involves Strength or Dexterity, and you can’t cast spells.

***Armor Class (AC).*** Armor protects its wearer from attacks. The armor (and shield) you wear determines your base Armor Class.

\column

<br><br>

***Heavy Armor.*** Heavier armor interferes with the wearer’s ability to move quickly, stealthily, and freely. If the Armor table shows “Str 13” or “Str 15” in the Strength column for an armor type, the armor reduces the wearer's speed by 10 feet unless the wearer has a Strength score equal to or higher than the listed score. 

***Stealth.*** If the Armor table shows “Disadvantage” in the Stealth column, the wearer has disadvantage on Dexterity (Stealth) checks.

***Shields.*** Shields are made from a variety of materials, ranging from thick beetle shells to mekillot plates to reinforced bark, and are carried in one hand.

Any classes that would have proficiency with shields have proficiency with Simple Shields by default.

If you have proficiency with shields and martial weapons, you have proficiency with Martial Shields.

You can benefit from only one shield at a time.

<img src='https://i.ibb.co/Jj2ZZFX/Armor-and-shields.png' style='position:relative; top:130px; left:-415px; height:400px; width:800px;mix-blend-mode:multiply' >


{{pageNumber,auto}}
\page

### Light Armor
The lightest and cheapest option, worn by most Athasians, designed to trap moisture and maximize air flow.

Made from supple and thin materials, light armor favors agile adventurers since it offers some protection without sacrificing mobility. If you wear light armor, you add your Dexterity modifier to the base number from your armor type to determine your Armor Class.

***Padded.*** Commonly made by layering oiled canvas between silk, with a soft padding underneath. *Types:* kes'trekel feather, spidersilk, giantweave.

***Leather.*** The breastplate and shoulder protectors of this armor are made of leather that has been stiffened by being boiled in oil. The rest of the armor is made of softer and more flexible materials. *Types:* inix, baazrag, jhakarskin.

***Studded Leather.*** Made from tough but flexible leather, studded leather is reinforced with close-set rivets or spikes made of bone or chitin.

### Medium Armor
More protection with less flexibility, more often used in cities than in the direct sun but also built with ventilation in mind allowing some to avoid overheating during exertion. If you wear medium armor, you add your Dexterity modifier, to a maximum of +2, to the base number from your armor type to determine your Armor Class.

***Hide.*** Crude but flexible enough for use in the sun, favored by many warriors. *Types:* tembo, kank, kirre, mekillot.

***Bone Mail.*** Stiff leather jackets adorned with small disks or squares of horn, bone, or wood. The kank and the cilops have hard body parts ideal for such coats. 

***Scale Mail.*** A heavy coat with carru leather leggings (and perhaps a seperate skirt), covered with the overlapping scales of a beast. The suit includes gauntlets. *Types:* scorpion, mekillot.

***Shell Breastplate.*** Fitted inix or mekillot shell pieces worn over supple leather. Legs and arms are left vulnerable but the vital organs are protected and movement unhampered. 

***Chitin Half Plate.*** Shaped chitin plates covering most of the body except the leg, which is protected by simple greaves held together by leather straps.

{{note
##### Armor and Extreme Heat
Extreme heat rules (see Chapter 7) will almost always apply every day in Athas. Characters exposed to the heat <u>and without access to water</u> must make a Constitution saving throw at the end of each hour of exposure (DC 5 + 1 per hour after first) or gain a level of exhaustion. Those wearing Medium or Heavy armors have disadvantage on this save.

Anyone foolish enough to wear metal armor in extreme heat also requires double their normal allotment of water.
}}



### Heavy Armor
Of all the armor categories, heavy armor offers the best protection. These suits of armor cover the entire body and are designed to stop a wide range of attacks. Only proficient warriors can manage their weight and bulk.

Heavy armor doesn’t let you add your Dexterity modifier to your Armor Class, but it also doesn’t penalize you if your Dexterity modifier is negative.

Years of experimentation and clever crafting methods have led armorers to develop ingenious air ventilation and circulation methods allowing alternative armors to be worn in the heat of Athas, albeit with some drawback.


***Baazrag Mail.*** Hardened leather with the thick bones of boneclaw baazrags sewn within. While appearing massive and imposing, it is the least practical of the heavy armors.

***So-ut Mail.*** The scales of a so-ut are attached to a layer of quilted fabric worn underneath to prevent chafing and cushion blows. The hard scales provide superior protection to traditional scale armor.

***Mastyrial Splint Mail.*** The chitinous shell of the mastyrial is valued for its protective qualities. This armor is made of narrow vertical strips of chitin riveted to a backing of leather over cloth padding, with flexible webbed hide protecting the joints.

***Braxat Plate.*** Braxat shell makes excellent armor plates that can be shaped to fit the body and interlocked. A suit of braxat plate includes gauntlets, greaves, a visored helmet, and thick padding underneath to cushion attacks. Buckles and straps  distribute the weight across your body. 

### Getting Into and Out of Armor
The time it takes to don or doff armor depends on the armor’s category. If you have help, reduce this time by half.

***Don.*** This is the time it takes to put on armor. You benefit from the armor's AC only if you take the full time to don the suit of armor.

***Doff.*** This is the time it takes to take off armor. 



{{classTable,frame,decoration
##### Donning and Doffing Armor and Shields
| Category       | Don         | Doff       |
|:---------------|:-----------:|:----------:|
| *Armor* | | |
| &emsp;Light Armor    | 1 minute    | 1 minute   |
| &emsp;Medium Armor   | 5 minutes   | 1 minute   |
| &emsp;Heavy Armor    | 10 minutes  | 5 minutes  |
| *Shields* | | |
| &emsp;Buckler        | 1 bonus action    | 1 bonus action   |
| &emsp;Focus Shield   | 1 bonus action    | 1 bonus action   |
| &emsp;Spiked Shield  | 1 bonus action    | 1 bonus action   |
| &emsp;Target Shield  | 1 bonus action    | 1 bonus action   |
| &emsp;Kite Shield    | 1 action    | 1 action   |
| &emsp;Tower Shield   | 1 action    | 1 action   |
}}


{{pageNumber,auto}}
\page

### Simple Shields
Simple shields are held by straps or a handle attached on one side, and used as basic protection against blows or missiles.

***Buckler.*** A buckler is made from thin wood, often overlaid with leather and braced with some kind of hide or chitin. It is an inexpensive and easy to make shield option, making it popular in every class of society.

Wielding a buckler increases your Armor Class by 1 against melee weapon attacks only.

***Focus Shield.*** The focus shield appears as a type of bracer which draws upon a spellcaster's arcane energy to create a small defensive field and act in place of an arcane focus. They are often issued to Templars but are extremely rare to see on non-sanctioned spellcasters, not least of all because of the attention it can bring upon the wielder. 

You may not wield a focus, weapon, or other object in the hand with a focus shield, but you may still make ability checks and skill checks as if your hand was empty.

The focus shield can act as a spellcasting focus, even for classes that normally cannot use shields as a focus.

You may not use a focus shield if you are wearing medium or heavy armor.

### Martial Shields
Martial shields have a more specific purpose than basic defense, and are thus equipped by experienced users.

***Spiked Shield.*** A spiked shield is made from wood or bone, and contains either a single large spike protruding from its boss or numerous smaller spikes placed closer to the edges.

A spiked shield counts as a melee weapon with the light property, dealing 2 piercing damage.

***Target Shield.*** A target shield is a large, round shield typically used by soldiers to guard against arrows or heavy blows. They are designed to resist splitting, making them pricier and less common outside of the city-states.

***Kite Shield.*** A kite shield is a large leaf-shaped shield designed for mounted combatants, with a rounded top and narrow, pointed bottom.

If you are attacked by a creature with a melee attack, but the attack does not hit, you may expend your reaction to make an opposed Strength check against the creature. If successful, you knock the creature off balance, giving the next attack against them advantage.

If you are mounted, you may add +1 to your mount's armor class.

***Tower Shield.*** A tower shield is a large, rectangular shield often used as portable cover. 

While wielding a tower shield, you cannot cast spells, and you have disadvantage on ability checks, saving throws, and attack rolls you make that involve Strength or Dexterity.

As an action, you can plant the tower shield on the ground using its built-in stand, or lift it up and wield it as a shield. The wielder and one other creature can use the planted shield as three-quarters cover. 

Small or Tiny creatures cannot wield tower shields.

