| Bottle                 | 1 1/2 pints liquid                |
| Bucket                 | 3 gallons liquid, 1/2 cubic foot solid                |
| Chest                 | 12 cubic feet/300 pounds of gear                |
| Flask or tankard                 | 1 pint liquid               |
| Jug or pitcher                 | 1 gallon liquid                |
| Pot                 | 1 gallon liquid                |
| Pouch                 | 1/5 cubic foot/6 pounds of gear                |
| Sack                 | 1 cubic foot/30 pounds of gear                |
| Vial                 | 4 ounces liquid                |
| Waterskin                 | 4 pints liquid                |

\* You can also strap items, such as a bedroll or a coil of rope, to the outside of a backpack.
}}



 {{width:7px}} ***Potion of Healing.*** A character who drinks the magical red fluid in this vial regains 2d4 + 2 hit points. Administering a potion to another character takes an action and requires the imbiber to roll for healing, but characters have the choice of using an action or a bonus action when drinking a potion themselves. If taking an action, the potion automatically heals the maximum amount of points; on a bonus action, roll as normal. 

***Pouch.*** A cloth or leather pouch can hold up to 20 sling bullets or 50 blowgun needles, among other things. A compartmentalized pouch for holding spell components is called a component pouch (described earlier in this section).

***Quiver.*** A quiver can hold up to 20 arrows.

***Ram, Portable.*** You can use a portable ram to break down doors. When doing so, you gain a +4 bonus on the Strength check. One other character can help you use the ram, giving you advantage on this check.

***Rations.*** Rations consist of dry foods suitable for extended travel, including jerky, dried fruit, hardtack, and nuts.

***Rope.*** Rope, whether made of hemp or silk, has 2 hit points and can be burst with a DC 17 Strength check.

***Scale, Merchant’s.*** A scale includes a small balance, pans, and a suitable assortment of weights up to 2 pounds. With it, you can measure the exact weight of small objects, such as raw precious metals or trade goods, to help determine their worth.

***Silt Mask.*** A filtered and ventilated mask formed from insectoid webbing and animal hides. While wearing a silt mask, you have advantage on all checks made to resist suffocation effects from the Gray Death. 

***Spellbook.*** Essential for Arcanists, a spellbook is a leather-bound tome with 100 blank vellum pages suitable for recording spells.

***Splash-globes.*** Splash‐globes are spherical glass jars containing contact poison or up to half a pint of alchemical fluid. In addition to bursting on impact like any grenade, splash‐globes can be placed in hinged pelota, thus giving the grenade additional range when launched from a splashbow or dejada. 

***Spyglass.*** Objects viewed through a spyglass are magnified to twice their size.

***Tent.*** A simple and portable canvas shelter. A tent sleeps two.

***Tinderbox.*** This small container holds flint, striker, and tinder (usually dry cloth soaked in light oil) used to kindle a fire. Using it to light a torch—or anything else with abundant, exposed fuel—takes an action. Lighting any other fire takes 1 minute.

***Torch.*** A torch burns for 1 hour, providing bright light in a 20-foot radius and dim light for an additional 20 feet. If you make a melee attack with a burning torch and hit, it deals 1 fire damage.


{{note
##### Equipment Packs
Most people avoid cumbersome equipment packs in the heat of the desert. Still, some items are vital for one's travels to such inhospitable lands.The starting equipment you get from your class includes a collection of useful adventuring gear, put together in a pack. The contents of these packs are listed here. If you are buying your starting equipment, you can purchase a pack for the price shown, which might be cheaper than buying the items individually.

***Burglar’s Pack (16 ct).*** Includes a backpack, a crowbar, 10 feet of string, a bell, 5 candles, a bag of bone caltrops, a tinderbox, a bone grappling hook, 2 flasks of oil, 5 days' rations, and a waterskin. The pack also has 50 feet of hempen rope strapped to the side of it.
 
***Diplomat's Pack (39 ct).*** Includes a chest, 2 cases for maps and scrolls, a set of fine clothes, a bottle of ink, an ink quill, a lamp, 2 flasks of oil, 5 sheets of parchment, a vial of perfume, sealing wax, and soap.

***Dune Trader’s Pack (12 ct).*** Includes a backpack, an abacus, a blanket, a lamp, a flask of oil, a pouch, a sack, a merchant's tunic, 2 ceramic vials, and two waterskins.

***Entertainer’s Pack (40 ct).*** Includes a backpack, a bedroll, 2 costumes, 5 candles, 5 days of rations, a waterskin, and a disguise kit.

***Explorer’s Pack (10 ct).*** Includes a backpack, a bedroll, a mess kit, a tinderbox, 10 torches, 10 days of rations, a two-person tent, a set of desert clothes, and 2 waterskins. The pack also has 50 feet of hempen rope strapped to the side of it.

***Priest’s Pack (19 ct).*** Includes a backpack, a blanket, 10 candles, a tinderbox, an alms box, 2 blocks of incense, a censer, vestments, 2 days of rations, and a waterskin.

***Scholar’s Pack (40 ct).*** Includes a backpack, a bedroll, a book of lore, a bottle of ink, an ink quill, 10 sheets of parchment, a small knife, 5 days' rations, and a waterskin.
}}




